Final Project - DTSA 5011

Problem Statement

I want to explore different object detection algorithms on the VisDrone dataset, which is primarily for cars, bus, trucks, people, etc captured from various drones between 25-400 ft. AGL. My goal is to find a training strategy that performs well on this dataset so I can use it with my own personal drone.

  • Data Source:

    • https://github.com/VisDrone/VisDrone-Dataset
    • Train
      • https://drive.google.com/file/d/1a2oHjcEcwXP8oUF95qiwrqzACb2YlUhn/view?usp=sharing
    • Valid
      • https://drive.google.com/file/d/1bxK5zgLn0_L8x276eKkuYA_FzwCIjb59/view?usp=sharing

  • Data Details

    • I am using the Task 1 object detection in images challenge data. The task is to detect objects of certain categories:
      • car
      • bus
      • truck
      • pedestrian
      • awning-tricycle
      • ignored_regions
      • people
      • motor
      • bicycle
      • tricycle
      • van
      • others
    • There are over 7000 images with over 393,666 instances of objects in them.
  • This VisDrone dataset description comes from:
    • https://github.com/VisDrone/VisDrone2018-DET-toolkit
<bbox_left>,<bbox_top>,<bbox_width>,<bbox_height>,<score>,<object_category>,<truncation>,<occlusion>


    Name                                                  Description
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------     
 <bbox_left>	     The x coordinate of the top-left corner of the predicted bounding box

 <bbox_top>	     The y coordinate of the top-left corner of the predicted object bounding box

 <bbox_width>	     The width in pixels of the predicted object bounding box

<bbox_height>	     The height in pixels of the predicted object bounding box

   <score>	     The score in the DETECTION file indicates the confidence of the predicted bounding box enclosing 
                     an object instance.
                     The score in GROUNDTRUTH file is set to 1 or 0. 1 indicates the bounding box is considered in evaluation, 
                     while 0 indicates the bounding box will be ignored.
                      
<object_category>    The object category indicates the type of annotated object, (i.e., ignored regions(0), pedestrian(1), 
                     people(2), bicycle(3), car(4), van(5), truck(6), tricycle(7), awning-tricycle(8), bus(9), motor(10), 
                     others(11))
                      
<truncation>	     The score in the DETECTION result file should be set to the constant -1.
                     The score in the GROUNDTRUTH file indicates the degree of object parts appears outside a frame 
                     (i.e., no truncation = 0 (truncation ratio 0%), and partial truncation = 1 (truncation ratio 1% ~ 50%)).
                      
<occlusion>	     The score in the DETECTION file should be set to the constant -1.
                     The score in the GROUNDTRUTH file indicates the fraction of objects being occluded (i.e., no occlusion = 0 
                     (occlusion ratio 0%), partial occlusion = 1 (occlusion ratio 1% ~ 50%), and heavy occlusion = 2 
                     (occlusion ratio 50% ~ 100%)).

  • We will create a function to help us read in the annotation files for each image following the format from the VisDrone dataset.
  • The annotation files for VisDrone are originally comma separated, so we will split on the comma and parse in the following order:

    • left

      • The x coordinate of the top-left corner of the predicted bounding box

    • top

      • The y coordinate of the top-left corner of the predicted object bounding box

    • w

      • The width in pixels of the predicted object bounding box

    • h

      • The height in pixels of the predicted object bounding box

    • score_i

      • The score in the DETECTION file indicates the confidence of the predicted bounding box enclosing an object instance.
      • The score in GROUNDTRUTH file is set to 1 or 0. 1 indicates the bounding box is considered in evaluation, while 0 indicates the bounding box will be ignored.

    • cat_i

      • The object category indicates the type of annotated object,
        • ignored regions(0),
        • pedestrian(1),
        • people(2),
        • bicycle(3),
        • car(4),
        • van(5),
        • truck(6),
        • tricycle(7),
        • awning-tricycle(8),
        • bus(9),
        • motor(10),
        • others(11)

    • trunc_i

      • The score in the DETECTION result file should be set to the constant -1.
      • The score in the GROUNDTRUTH file indicates the degree of object parts appears outside a frame (i.e., no truncation = 0 (truncation ratio 0%), and partial truncation = 1 (truncation ratio 1% ~ 50%)).

    • occ_i

      • The score in the DETECTION file should be set to the constant -1.
      • The score in the GROUNDTRUTH file indicates the fraction of objects being occluded (i.e., no occlusion = 0 (occlusion ratio 0%), partial occlusion = 1 (occlusion ratio 1% ~ 50%), and heavy occlusion = 2 (occlusion ratio 50% ~ 100%)).
  • We want to convert the VisDrone format to YOLO format.
    • YOLO format is a space seperated line by line .txt file per each image that contains all of the bounding boxes in each file.
    • Each image will have a single .txt file that should have the following for lines for each object in it separated by space:
    • Example, yolo_line = f"{int(cat_i)} {xc_n} {yc_n} {w_n} {h_n}"
      • cat_i
        • The object category similar format as VisDrone cat_i
      • xc_n
        • The normalized center point on the x-axis of the object (i.e. (xmin+xmax)/(image_width * 2.0))
      • yc_n
        • The normalized center point on the y-axis of the object (i.e. (ymin+ymax)/(image_height * 2.0))
      • w_n
        • The normalized width of the bounding box (i.e. (w/image_width))
      • h_n
        • The normalized height of the bounding box (i.e. (h/image_height))
  • We will create a Pandas DataFrame of our data read and save off to .csv for time saving later:
    • df_train.csv
      • The training images/annotations from VisDrone read in and converted into YOLO format.
    • df_val.csv
      • The validation images/annotations from VisDrone read in and converted into YOLO format.
In[5]:
def read_in_VisDrone(img_list,classes):
    df = pd.DataFrame(columns=['img_path','img_h','img_w','xmin','xmax','ymin','ymax','left','top','w','h','score_i','cat_i','trunc_i','occ_i','label_i',"yolo_line"])
    for i, img_i in tqdm(enumerate(img_list)):
        anno_i = img_i.replace("images","annotations").split(".")[0]+".txt"
        f=open(anno_i)
        f_read=f.readlines()
        f.close()
        img_j = plt.imread(img_i)
        img_h,img_w,_ = img_j.shape
        for line in f_read:
            left,top,w,h,score_i,cat_i,trunc_i,occ_i=line.replace(',\n','').split(',')
            j = len(df)
            df.at[j,'img_path'] = img_i
            df.at[j,'left']=left
            df.at[j,'top']=top
            df.at[j,'w']=w
            df.at[j,'h']=h
            df.at[j,'score_i']=score_i
            df.at[j,'cat_i']=cat_i
            df.at[j,'trunc_i']=trunc_i
            df.at[j,'occ_i']=occ_i.strip()
            x1=float(left)
            x2=float(left)+float(w)
            y1=float(top)
            y2=float(top)+float(h)
            df.at[j,'xmin']=x1
            df.at[j,'xmax']=x2
            df.at[j,'ymin']=y1
            df.at[j,'ymax']=y2
            df.at[j,'label_i']=classes[int(cat_i)]
            xc = (x1+x2)/2.0
            yc = (y1+y2)/2.0
            xc_n = xc/img_w
            yc_n = yc/img_h
            df.at[j,'img_h']=img_h
            df.at[j,'img_w']=img_w
            w_n = float(w)/img_w
            h_n = float(h)/img_h
            yolo_line = f"{int(cat_i)} {xc_n} {yc_n} {w_n} {h_n}"
            df.at[j,"yolo_line"] = yolo_line
    return df

1.3 Create YOLO Training Data

  • We want to convert each of these instances into a YOLO .txt file for training/validation.
    • We need to make a single .txt file for each unique YOLO image.
      • So we will create a unique dataframe, df_i to temporarily hold the instances associated with a single image.
    • We will only create the .txt file if it doesn't exist in the output directory, VisDroneYOLO
In[9]:
path_VisDroneYOLO = "VisDroneYOLO"
if os.path.exists(path_VisDroneYOLO)==False:
    os.makedirs(path_VisDroneYOLO)
files_found=os.listdir(path_VisDroneYOLO)
val_imgs = [os.path.basename(w) for w in df_val["img_path"]]
val_annos = [w.split(".")[0]+".txt" for w in val_imgs]
for img_i  in tqdm(val_imgs):
    anno_i = img_i.split(".")[0]+".txt"
    if img_i not in files_found:
        img_i_abs_path = os.path.join(path_VisDrone_Yolo_Objs_val,"images",img_i)
        shutil.copy(img_i_abs_path,path_VisDroneYOLO)
    if anno_i not in files_found:
        img_i_abs_path = os.path.join(path_VisDrone_Yolo_Objs_val,"images",img_i)
        df_i = df_val[df_val["img_path"]==img_i_abs_path].copy()
        df_i = df_i.reset_index().drop("index",axis=1)
        yolo_file_i = ""
        for i in range(len(df_i)):
            if i==0:
                yolo_file_i = df_i.yolo_line.loc[i] + "\n"
            else:
                yolo_file_i = yolo_file_i + df_i.yolo_line.loc[i] + "\n"
        output_yolo_file_i = os.path.join(path_VisDroneYOLO,anno_i)
        with open(output_yolo_file_i,"w") as f:
            f.write(yolo_file_i)
train_imgs = [os.path.basename(w) for w in df_train["img_path"]]

  • Training YOLO can use single files for train, val, and test that go into the yaml file we have to make for training.
  • These files will contain the absolute path to our images.
    • Caution, each image absolute path should have a .txt file next to it in the directory it resides, but you don't have to write that to this file. YOLO knows how to find it from that image's absolute path.

def create_list_file(list_i,filename_i):
    with open(filename_i,"w") as f:
        for line in list_i:
            f.writelines(line+"\n")
path_train_list = "train_list.txt"
path_valid_list = "valid_list.txt"
path_test_list = "test_list.txt"
create_list_file(train_list,path_train_list)
create_list_file(val_list,path_valid_list)
create_list_file(test_list,path_test_list)

2.2 Model Matrix - Training

  • We will create multiple different models, exploring different algorithms and hyperparameters:
    • architecture
      • yolo11
        • Latest as of 10/24/2024 in Ultralytics for YOLO
        • Key Features (source https://docs.ultralytics.com/models/yolo11/#key-features)
          • Enhanced Feature Extraction: YOLO11 employs an improved backbone and neck architecture, which enhances feature extraction capabilities for more precise object detection and complex task performance.
          • Optimized for Efficiency and Speed: YOLO11 introduces refined architectural designs and optimized training pipelines, delivering faster processing speeds and maintaining an optimal balance between accuracy and performance.
          • Greater Accuracy with Fewer Parameters: With advancements in model design, YOLO11m achieves a higher mean Average Precision (mAP) on the COCO dataset while using 22% fewer parameters than YOLOv8m, making it computationally efficient without compromising accuracy.
          • Adaptability Across Environments: YOLO11 can be seamlessly deployed across various environments, including edge devices, cloud platforms, and systems supporting NVIDIA GPUs, ensuring maximum flexibility.
          • Broad Range of Supported Tasks: Whether it's object detection, instance segmentation, image classification, pose estimation, or oriented object detection (OBB), YOLO11 is designed to cater to a diverse set of computer vision challenges.
      • yolov10
        • Key Features (source https://docs.ultralytics.com/models/yolov10/#key-features)
          • NMS-Free Training: Utilizes consistent dual assignments to eliminate the need for NMS, reducing inference latency.
          • Holistic Model Design: Comprehensive optimization of various components from both efficiency and accuracy perspectives, including lightweight classification heads, spatial-channel decoupled down sampling, and rank-guided block design.
          • Enhanced Model Capabilities: Incorporates large-kernel convolutions and partial self-attention modules to improve performance without significant computational cost.
      • yolov8
        • Key Features (source https://docs.ultralytics.com/models/yolov8/#key-features)
          • Advanced Backbone and Neck Architectures: YOLOv8 employs state-of-the-art backbone and neck architectures, resulting in improved feature extraction and object detection performance.
          • Anchor-free Split Ultralytics Head: YOLOv8 adopts an anchor-free split Ultralytics head, which contributes to better accuracy and a more efficient detection process compared to anchor-based approaches.
          • Optimized Accuracy-Speed Tradeoff: With a focus on maintaining an optimal balance between accuracy and speed, YOLOv8 is suitable for real-time object detection tasks in diverse application areas.
          • Variety of Pre-trained Models: YOLOv8 offers a range of pre-trained models to cater to various tasks and performance requirements, making it easier to find the right model for your specific use case.
    • imgsz
      • 1280
      • 640
    • batch
      • 16 (default)
      • 4
      • 2
      • 1
    • Model Variants
      • s
        • small architecture
        • Balances speed and accuracy
      • m
        • medium architecture
        • general-purpose use
      • l
        • large architecture
        • higher accuracy at the cost of increased computational resources.

metrics = [
    'metrics/precision(B)', 'metrics/recall(B)', 'metrics/mAP50(B)', 'metrics/mAP50-95(B)', 
    'train/box_loss', 'train/cls_loss', 'train/dfl_loss', 
    'val/box_loss', 'val/cls_loss', 'val/dfl_loss'
]


df_extended = df.copy()
df_extended['input_size'] = df_extended['model'].apply(lambda x: '1280' if '1280' in x else '640')
df_extended['size_category'] = df_extended['model'].apply(
    lambda x: 'small' if 's_' in x else ('medium' if 'm_' in x else 'large')
)
df_extended['line_style'] = df_extended['size_category'].map({'small': '--', 'medium': '-.', 'large': '-'})
size_marker_map = {'small': 'o', 'medium': 's', 'large': 'D'} 


for metric in metrics:
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
    
    for (model, group) in df_extended.groupby('model'):
        plt.plot(
            group['epoch'], group[metric], 
            label=model, linestyle=group['line_style'].iloc[0], 
            marker=size_marker_map[group['size_category'].iloc[0]], 
            color=palette_extended[model]
        )
        
        # Add labels with spacing from the last data point
        plt.text(
            group['epoch'].iloc[-1] + 1.5, group[metric].iloc[-1], 
            model, verticalalignment='top', fontsize=9, color=palette_extended[model]
        )
    
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.title(f"Model Metrics - {metric.replace('_', ' ').title()}")
    plt.xlabel("Epoch")
    plt.ylabel(metric.replace('_', ' ').title())
    plt.legend(title='Model', bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left')
    plt.show()

4.0 Discussion/Conclusion

  • We were able to train several different object detection algorithms:
    • yolov8
    • yolov10
    • yolov11
  • We were able to explore different input sizes:
    • 1280
    • 640
  • We were able to look at varouos Model Variants:
    • s
      • small architecture
      • Balances speed and accuracy
    • m
      • medium architecture
      • general-purpose use
    • l
      • large architecture
      • higher accuracy at the cost of increased computational resources.
  • In conclusion, we FOUND that in general the larger Model Variant performed better across the different algorithms. In addition, we found that a larger input size gave us better performance for mAP (mean Average Precision), a metric used for assessing accuracy in object detection that balances precision of bounding boxes localization with their intersection over union to the target and the correctness of the class.
  • In the future, I could improve this process by applying more data augmentation strategies for increasing the diversity of my data and size of my data. I could also train even larger variants like the extra large and train with various other hyperparameter changes via a GridSearch.
  • Overall, I am happy with my results and feel like I made a good baseline model on the dataset using the state of the art (SOTA) algorithms, YOLOv11. I also was able to test it out with drone footage I have from my own drone and car! It detected my car well!
